2026-04-16 12:10:16 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module internal switch / series path between Control Input (+) and Control Output (+)'] hypothesis_explanation='12 V from the power supply reaches the control module input correctly (measured 12 V on Control Input (+) and 0 V on Control Input (−)), and the power‑supply indicator LED is on, so the supply is good and the polarity into the control module is correct. However, at the control module outputs we always see 0 V on both the (+) and (−) cables regardless of the switch position. That means the internal series path that should connect the positive input line through the switch to the positive output line is open (or miswired) in both switch positions, while the negative line appears tied to 0 V only locally. Since the red ‘inverted cables’ LED is off and no polarity inversion was detected by measurement, the inverted‑cables indicator path is not erroneously conducting, and the issue is confined to the main switched path. Therefore the most likely single fault is a failed or miswired internal switch/trace between Control Input (+) and Control Output (+) inside the control module. Repair or replace this internal switch path should restore 12 V to the load module and allow the lamp to function (assuming the downstream module is healthy).'
